    {
      "id": "42ba27afd2e693e853c155d955581370d7105824",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 301,
        "name": "Dmitry Eremin",
        "email": "dmitry.eremin@intel.com",
        "username": "dmiter",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2013-03-11 19:45:19.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 6:\n\nIt looks an unguarded access in obd_device_list_seq_show() also and many other places where class_name2obd() and class_uuid2obd() is used without proper locking. Do you care about them?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 6
    },
    {
      "id": "e12de31f289a46616b841ee61da5ebe5c829daa4",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 112,
        "name": "Oleg Drokin",
        "email": "green@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "green"
      },
      "date": "2013-03-12 05:08:35.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 6:\n\nWe definitely care about them.\nCan you come up with a patch?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 6
    },
    {
      "id": "a7c5addef5d599877feee253848ddf9107fead62",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 256,
        "name": "Hiroya Nozaki",
        "email": "nozaki.hiroya@jp.fujitsu.com",
        "username": "HiroyaNozaki"
      },
      "date": "2013-03-12 06:03:14.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 6:\n\nOf course, I'll definitely care about all problems related to what I done.\n\n> Can you come up with a patch?\nOK, I'll try to fix this problem too. please wait for a while.\n\nBy the way, Apparently all the procf entriese which handles an address to obd_device via PDE have the same kind of problems, like ... After when a procfs handler gets an address of obd_device via PDE, then next, lprocfs_obd_cleanup is invoked and the obd_device is freed ... this handler can access freed memory, so I think that we must not hand in an address of obd_device to procfs entries directly. And, instead of that, we should hand in obd->obd_minor. Because it makes a handler check lots of flags such as obd_stopping, obd_set_up and obd_attached before getting an obd_device address.\n\nIf it's true I'd like to make a new ticket for it.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 6
    },
    {
      "id": "3f4787523ec19c72801fa25eb2e294acea5dec93",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 256,
        "name": "Hiroya Nozaki",
        "email": "nozaki.hiroya@jp.fujitsu.com",
        "username": "HiroyaNozaki"
      },
      "date": "2013-03-18 05:58:51.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 6:\n\nHi, Oleg.\nThere're a lot more places than I expected. So ... I'd like to make 4 separated patches for modifying all the problems, like below.\n\n1) fix just the original problem, plus obd_device_list_seq_show().\n2) modify the places which call class_uuid2obd()\n3) modify the places which call class_num2obd()\n4) modify the places which call class_name2obd()\n\nMay I go along with this line?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 6
    },
    {
      "id": "0508c94903fd9a2ba580261d71d7d5d4a82bdc40",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 256,
        "name": "Hiroya Nozaki",
        "email": "nozaki.hiroya@jp.fujitsu.com",
        "username": "HiroyaNozaki"
      },
      "date": "2013-03-18 08:47:49.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 6:\n\nSorry again and again. I realized that these problems can not be handled separately. Anyway, I'll try to make the patch somehow.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 6
    },
    {
      "id": "6556a8ae341f15dc3735bf09a4e62064c8fb80d9",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 257,
        "name": "Keith Mannthey",
        "email": "keith.mannthey@intel.com",
        "username": "kmannth",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2013-04-19 15:40:36.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 6: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\nJust to be clear it seems there will be another patch.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 6
    },
